## Failure Recovery & Resilience

### Kubelet restart

- When kubelet restarts it deletes all existing Unix sockets under
  `/var/lib/kubelet/device-plugins/`.
- The plugin must detect this (e.g. by monitoring the socket file with an
  `fsnotify` watcher or by detecting the gRPC stream breaking) and
  re-register with the new kubelet instance. This means repeating Phase 2
  and Phase 3.

### Device failure

- When a device becomes unhealthy, update its `Health` field to
  `pluginapi.Unhealthy` and send the full updated device list via the
  `ListAndWatch` stream.
- Kubelet will decrease the allocatable count for the resource but will not
  evict existing pods using the device.

### Plugin failure

- If the plugin crashes, kubelet removes the resource from node capacity.
- Pods already running with allocated devices are **not** terminated.
- New pods requesting the resource cannot be scheduled until the plugin
  re-registers.

